---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
    title="Blog — Probabilis"
    description="Introducing Probabilis: an AI research lab in Accra, Ghana, testing the limits of machine intelligence against real local problems."
>
    <section class="page-hero">
        <div class="container">
            <span class="section-label">Blog</span>
            <h1 class="page-title">Lab Notes</h1>
            <p class="page-subtitle">
                Thoughts, reflections, and updates from our journey building AI
                research from Ghana.
            </p>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section article-section">
        <div class="container">
            <article class="article-wrapper">
                <div class="article-header">
                    <span class="article-tag">Lab News</span>
                    <span class="article-date">March 2026</span>
                </div>
                <h2 class="article-title">
                    Introducing Probabilis: AI Research from Accra
                </h2>
                <p class="article-read-time">5 min read</p>

                <div class="article-body">
                    <p>
                        There's a question that drives everything we do at
                        Probabilis: <strong
                            >is generative AI truly intelligent—or is it just
                            very good at pattern-matching?</strong
                        >
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Most AI research tries to answer this with benchmarks—
                        standardised tests designed in labs far removed from the
                        realities of everyday life. But we believe the most
                        honest way to test intelligence is to confront it with
                        <em>real problems</em>, in contexts where we already
                        understand the ground truth.
                    </p>

                    <h3>Why Ghana?</h3>

                    <p>
                        Ghana is navigating some of the most complex,
                        interconnected challenges on the continent. Annual
                        flooding devastates communities across Accra because of
                        inadequate urban planning and sanitation infrastructure.
                        Healthcare and education remain deeply unequal between
                        urban centres and rural areas. The economy is under
                        strain—high inflation, a weakening currency, and
                        crushing debt have prompted an IMF stabilisation
                        programme. Youth unemployment exceeds 13%, driven by a
                        widening gap between what schools teach and what
                        industries need. The power grid, plagued by the
                        phenomenon Ghanaians know as <em>dumsor</em>, remains
                        unreliable. Illegal mining—<em>galamsey</em>—is
                        destroying rivers, forests, and farmland at an alarming
                        rate. And governance challenges, from corruption to
                        institutional opacity, undermine progress at every
                        level.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        These are not abstract problems. They are tangible,
                        measurable, and deeply felt. That makes them
                        <strong>ideal testbeds for AI</strong>.
                    </p>

                    <h3>What We Do</h3>

                    <p>
                        At Probabilis, we treat generative AI not as a
                        solution—but as a
                        <strong>hypothesis</strong>. We take the problems Ghana
                        faces every day and ask: can these models actually
                        reason about them? Can they help predict flood risk from
                        drainage data? Can they reason about energy demand on an
                        unstable grid? Can they assist in allocating healthcare
                        resources to underserved communities?
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        By grounding our research in locally verifiable
                        contexts, we can clearly see where models succeed—and,
                        more importantly, where they fail. This isn't
                        benchmarking for the sake of leaderboards. It's research
                        designed to produce insight that matters.
                    </p>

                    <h3>Our Goals</h3>

                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <strong>Build rigorous evaluation frameworks</strong
                            >
                            that test AI against real Ghanaian challenges—not synthetic
                            benchmarks.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <strong>Develop local AI expertise</strong> by growing
                            a research lab rooted in Ghana, staffed by Ghanaian researchers
                            who understand the context firsthand.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <strong>Contribute to global AI discourse</strong>
                            by showing that meaningful evaluation requires diverse,
                            locally grounded perspectives—not just Western-centric
                            datasets.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <strong>Shape the future of AI in Ghana</strong> by demonstrating
                            how intelligent systems can—and cannot—address the country's
                            most pressing needs.
                        </li>
                    </ul>

                    <h3>Shaping the Future</h3>

                    <p>
                        We believe that the next chapter of AI won't be written
                        exclusively in Silicon Valley or Beijing. It will be
                        co-authored by researchers in Accra, Lagos, Nairobi, and
                        across the Global South—people who bring not just
                        technical skill, but lived understanding of the problems
                        AI claims to solve.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Probabilis is our contribution to that future. A small,
                        focused lab doing honest work—testing what these models
                        can really do, building from where we stand, and sharing
                        what we learn along the way.
                    </p>

                    <p class="article-closing">
                        We're just getting started. Follow along as we publish
                        our findings, share our methodology, and build something
                        meaningful from Accra.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </article>
        </div>
    </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
    .page-hero {
        padding-top: calc(var(--nav-height) + var(--space-5xl));
        padding-bottom: var(--space-2xl);
        text-align: center;
    }
    .page-title {
        font-size: var(--text-5xl);
        font-weight: 900;
        margin-bottom: var(--space-lg);
        background: var(--gradient-hero);
        -webkit-background-clip: text;
        background-clip: text;
        -webkit-text-fill-color: transparent;
    }
    .page-subtitle {
        font-size: var(--text-lg);
        color: var(--color-text-secondary);
        max-width: 600px;
        margin-inline: auto;
    }

    /* --- Article --- */
    .article-wrapper {
        max-width: 720px;
        margin-inline: auto;
    }
    .article-header {
        display: flex;
        justify-content: space-between;
        align-items: center;
        margin-bottom: var(--space-lg);
    }
    .article-tag {
        font-family: var(--font-mono);
        font-size: var(--text-xs);
        color: var(--color-accent);
        text-transform: uppercase;
        letter-spacing: 0.05em;
        padding: var(--space-xs) var(--space-sm);
        background: rgba(56, 189, 248, 0.08);
        border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
    }
    .article-date {
        font-size: var(--text-xs);
        color: var(--color-text-muted);
    }
    .article-title {
        font-size: var(--text-3xl);
        font-weight: 800;
        line-height: 1.25;
        margin-bottom: var(--space-sm);
        color: var(--color-text-primary);
    }
    .article-read-time {
        font-size: var(--text-xs);
        color: var(--color-text-muted);
        margin-bottom: var(--space-2xl);
        padding-bottom: var(--space-2xl);
        border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    }

    /* --- Article Body --- */
    .article-body p {
        font-size: var(--text-base);
        color: var(--color-text-secondary);
        line-height: 1.9;
        margin-bottom: var(--space-lg);
    }
    .article-body strong {
        color: var(--color-text-primary);
    }
    .article-body em {
        color: var(--color-accent);
        font-style: italic;
    }
    .article-body h3 {
        font-size: var(--text-xl);
        font-weight: 700;
        color: var(--color-text-primary);
        margin-top: var(--space-2xl);
        margin-bottom: var(--space-md);
    }
    .article-body ul {
        list-style: none;
        padding: 0;
        margin-bottom: var(--space-xl);
    }
    .article-body ul li {
        position: relative;
        padding-left: var(--space-xl);
        font-size: var(--text-base);
        color: var(--color-text-secondary);
        line-height: 1.8;
        margin-bottom: var(--space-md);
    }
    .article-body ul li::before {
        content: "→";
        position: absolute;
        left: 0;
        color: var(--color-accent);
        font-weight: 700;
    }
    .article-closing {
        margin-top: var(--space-xl);
        padding-top: var(--space-xl);
        border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border);
        font-style: italic;
        color: var(--color-text-muted) !important;
    }

    @media (max-width: 768px) {
        .page-title {
            font-size: var(--text-3xl);
        }
        .article-title {
            font-size: var(--text-2xl);
        }
    }
</style>
